        <comment>
  <id>14676</id>
  <body><![CDATA[A toast to Bill Watterson! Humanist treasure. That was the last gasp of truly brilliant funny pages comics.<br /><br />Another two cents for Emma...<br /><br />You might want to take a look the big red collection of Windsor McCay's <i>Little Nemo In Slumberland</i> strips. They're still awe-inspiring, even a hundred years later. And charming. And adorable. Chris Ware, Moebius, Watterson, and countless others learned a LOT from him:<br /><br /><a target="_blank" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Little_Nemo" rel="nofollow">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Little_Nemo</a><br /><br />Based on your preferences, I'd say Alan Moore's run of <i>Swamp Thing</i> should be considered. Don't be deterred by its categorization as a horror title... it definitely has roots there (woohoo! EC Comics!), but Moore revamped it into a very different beastie. <br /><br />He took over the faltering DC run early in his career, and it definitely changed the playing field for comics. For one thing, it was the first title to ditch the frumpy Comics Code Authority and gear itself cater to adult readers (not in a porn way). <br /><br />I'll even go so far as to say it was groundbreaking (an adjective more commonly reserved for his later works like <i><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/472331.Watchmen" title="Watchmen by Alan Moore" rel="nofollow">Watchmen</a>, From Hell,</i> and <i>V for Vendetta</i>). I love, love, love <i>Swamp Thing</i>. It's also one of my favorite love stories. (The "Rites of Spring" issue where Swamp Thing and Abby finally kinda sorta "do it" is deeeelightful!)<br /><br />I brought up Moore in my original review of <i>The DaVinci Choad</i> specifically because, in my opinion, he truly IS subversive and eye-opening in his approach to storytelling/teaching, rather than a mindless regurgitator. (Woops... am I being elitist again? Oh well. Hopefully that Ryan guy isn't still reading this thread, poor bastard.)<br /><br />ANYhoo.<br /><br /> Moore is THE iconoclast of this wacky hierolyphics-based medium we're all so crazy about. I humbly suggest you check him out.<br /><br />Oh yeah, and RPG stands for Role Playing Game. NERRRRD UUUUUP.]]></body>
  
