  <body><![CDATA[OMG. My ribs hurt.<br /><br />Picture this - I came into the office this morning (glorified shed, views over fields, birds doing their singing and nesting thing outside, pretty cold &amp; gloomy today) - a little late after a small 'domestic' with my partner (joy) - a little bit grumpy and not particularly looking forward to the contents of my Inbox (it's going to be 99% customers, which is all good but not v exciting), and the first email I actually notice is that Mer has left a comment for me on Goodreads. Hmmm. Thinking that this da-vinci-comic thread has long since died, I wonder whether Mer has (please God, no) espied one of my lame, half-assed comments on another unworthy tome and has wielded her keys again to bring down the wrath of the Bodleian gods onto my quivering excuse for nascent literary ambition. But no. Alas, alack, poor Ryan.<br /><br />Poor, poor Ryan. Not only did he unwittingly engage (with some pretty feeble arguments) a Grand Master of verbal mordancy - and, groan, her buddies - but then, seemingly hungry to have more coals of 'public' humiliation heaped onto his already singed head, went and deleted all his comments, thus drawing attention to himself once more. Brendan may be right in thinking that he just came to his senses and realised that he had gone a little too far in the heat of the moment, and I don't know that the guy is necessarily a coward? Whichever way you look at it though, it can't feel good to be given a good verbal kicking and then laughed at, even online, by a bunch of people you don't even know and who clearly have bigger and better verbal boots with which to kick than you. I can't help but feel pity for him.<br /><br />So, even though I feel an *ickle* bit bad about this, I didn't feel so bad that I didn't kick back from my little desk with my cloudy view this morning and laugh out loud at the comments above. Mer, you really brightened my morning :)]]></body>
  
